Logistic Regression via FFNN (Feedforward Neural Network)

By Barry Daemi

     The objective was to implement an logistic regression classifier via forwardfeed neural network (FFNN), the purpose was to utilize said model in a real-world classification problem, a credit approval problem, which is the problem of which applicant to approve for credit, and which applicant to delcine credit. For the desire of making this implementation as comprehensible as possible, we tried to choice self-evident and self-descriptive names for each object and class name, and furthermore only utilized open-source Python packages. As just mentioned, the following Python packages found below are all open-sourced and publically available to anyone, whom has access to a computer and internet access.

     For the purpose of making implementation comprehensible and the execution simple, we choice to code in an object-oriented programming formate. For that reason we were able to contain the whole FFNN algorithm into a single class contained in the following code block. As good practice, we defined a function named __init__, which initializes the necessary objects critical for the function of an algorithm; this function is called an initialization function. With any neural network we split the forward and backward propagation phases into two different defined functions, forward_propagation() and backward_propagation in the neural network class, Neural_Network.
      To keep tract of the neural network learning, we created the function compute_cost() to computate the analytical cost at each thousand iterations of the training phase of the algorithm. To faciliate learning in the neural network, the object parametered need to be updated after each execution (e.g. iteration) of the network; for that we created a function update_parameters, which updated each of the object parameters through a gradient descent algorithm. To actually train the neural network, we created a train function that completed said task, while returning the trained neural network's object parameters for the predict function, that computes the train neural networks predictions.

class Neural_Network:
    
    # Initiates the paremeters and activiation function 
    def __init__(self,inputnodes,hiddennodes,outputnodes,learningrate):
        # Set numbers of nodes in each layer
        self.inodes=inputnodes;
        self.hnodes=hiddennodes;
        self.onodes=outputnodes;
        
        # Generates two weight matrices of size (hnodes1 by inodes), (hnodes2 by hnodes1) and (onodes by hnodes2)
        # through a normal PRN of N(mu=0,sigma^2=inodes^-0.5), N(mu=0,sigma^2=hnodes1^-0.5), and N(mu=0,sigma^2=hnodes2^-0.5)
        #self.wih=np.random.normal(0.0,pow(self.inodes,-0.5),(self.hnodes,self.inodes));
        self.wih=np.random.randn(self.hnodes,self.inodes);
        self.b1=np.zeros((self.hnodes,1));
        #self.who=np.random.normal(0.0,pow(self.hnodes,-0.5),(self.onodes,self.hnodes));
        self.who=np.random.randn(self.onodes,self.hnodes);
        self.b2=np.zeros((self.onodes,1));

        
        print("Wih = ");
        print(self.wih);
        print(" ");
        print("who = ");
        print(self.who);
        
        # Learning rate of the Neural Network
        self.lr=learningrate;
        
        # Retrieves sigmoid activation function from scipy.special
        self.activation_function=lambda x: sp.expit(x);
        
        pass
    
    # Trians the Neural Network
    def forward_propagation(self,inputs):
        # Calculates the signals inputted in Hidden Layer 1 
        hidden_inputs=np.dot(self.wih,inputs)+self.b1;
        hidden_outputs=self.activation_function(hidden_inputs);
        
        # Calculates signal inputted in Output Layer
        final_inputs=np.dot(self.who,hidden_outputs)+self.b2;
        final_outputs=self.activation_function(final_inputs);
        
        self.hiddeninputs=hidden_inputs;  self.hiddenoutputs=hidden_outputs;
        self.finalinputs=final_inputs;    self.finaloutputs=final_outputs;
        
        pass
    
    def forward_propagation2(self,X,parameters):
        W1=parameters["W1"];
        b1=parameters["b1"];
        W2=parameters["W2"];
        b2=parameters["b2"];
    
        # Implement Forward Propagation to calculate A2 (probabilities)
        Z1=np.dot(W1,X)+b1;
        A1=self.activation_function(Z1);
        Z2=np.dot(W2,A1)+b2;
        A2=self.activation_function(Z2);
    
        assert(A2.shape==(1,X.shape[1]));
    
        # Values needed in the backpropagation are stored in "cache". 
        # This will be given as an input to the backpropagation
        cache = {"Z1": Z1,
                 "A1": A1,
                 "Z2": Z2,
                 "A2": A2}
    
        return A2, cache;
    
    def backward_propagation(self,inputs,targets):
        m=inputs.shape[1];
        
        dZ_2=self.finaloutputs-targets;
        dW_2=(1/m)*np.dot(dZ_2,self.hiddenoutputs.T);
        db_2=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_2,axis=1,keepdims=True));
        dZ_1=np.dot(self.who.T,dZ_2)*(1-self.hiddenoutputs**2);
        dW_1=(1/m)*(np.dot(dZ_1,inputs.T));
        db_1=(1/m)*(np.sum(dZ_1,axis=1,keepdims=True));
        
        self.dW1=dW_1; self.db1=db_1; self.dW2=dW_2; self.db2=db_2;
        
        pass
    
    def compute_cost(self,Y):
        m=Y.shape[0];
        
        logprobs=np.multiply(Y,np.log(self.finaloutputs))+np.multiply((1-Y),np.log(1-self.finaloutputs));
        cost=(-1/m)*np.sum(logprobs);
        
        cost=float(np.squeeze(cost));
        
        assert(isinstance(cost,float));
        
        return cost;
    
    def update_parameters(self):
        self.wih=self.wih-self.lr*self.dW1;
        self.b1=self.b1-self.lr*self.db1;
        self.who=self.who-self.lr*self.dW2;
        self.b2=self.b2-self.lr*self.db2;
    
        pass
    
    def predict(self,x,parameters):
        A2,cache=n.forward_propagation2(x,parameters);
        predictions=(A2 > 0.5)
        
        return predictions;

    def train(self,inputs,targets,MaxIter=10000,print_cost=True):
        
        for i in range(0,MaxIter):
            n.forward_propagation(inputs);
            cost=n.compute_cost(targets);
            n.backward_propagation(inputs,targets);
            n.update_parameters();
            if print_cost and i % 1000 == 0:
                print("Cost after iteration %i: %f"%(i,cost));
        
        parameters={"W1": self.wih,
                  "b1": self.b1,
                  "W2": self.who,
                  "b2": self.b2}       
        
        return parameters;

     Instead of proceeding to the real-world problem, lets first address a simulated classification problem generated through pseudo-random number generation. In this simulated problem the algorithm will try to learn how to classify spiral data made up of red and purple points plot against their $(x,y)$ coordinates on a scatter plot.
     To generate the simulated data, we had to utilized the parameter form of a circle equation, where x-coordinates are mapped through $x(t)=r*cos(t)$, and the y-coordinates are mapped through $y(t)=r*sin(t)$. To generate the radius of the circle, we utilized linspace(), which created numpy array of four-hundred elements from $0$ to $1$. To generate variation in the spiral, a normally distributed prn algorithm, np.random.randn() was utilized to generate an added normal variation to each of the points angles.

N=400; # number of points per class 
D=2; # dimensionality 
K=2; # number of spiral arms

X=np.zeros((N*K,D)); # data matrix (each row = single example)
Y=np.zeros(N*K,dtype='int'); # class labels

for j in range(K):
    ix=range(N*j,N*(j+1));
    r=np.linspace(0,1,N); # radius
    t=np.linspace(j*4.2,(j+1)*4.2,N)+np.random.randn(N)*0.2; # theta
    X[ix]=np.c_[r*np.sin(t), r*np.cos(t)];
    Y[ix]=(0 if j%2==0 else 1);

X=copy.deepcopy(X.T);
Y=copy.deepcopy(Y.reshape(-1,1).T);

fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(8,8));

ax.set_title('Spiral Data');

     Since the inputs are of two-dimension, we had to generate two input nodes to feed the data into the neural network. While the target (e.g. the variable we are trying to explain) is of one-dimension, we had to only generate one output layer node to output the neural networks result. In regards to the hidden layer, we choice to generate four nodes. There is no explicit rules, or mathematical explanations at the current time that can reasonably explain why certain nerual network configurations is better or worest then other configurations; so at the present-date the current approach to optimizes neural network configuration is through trial and error. In regards to learning rate, it is the rate of which the neural network 'learns', or in other term, the rate at which it to adjust the weight matrices and bias vectors that determines the strength of connection between nodes. A good rule is that the learning rate, $\alpha$, should be between $0 \geq \alpha < 2$, but never greater than 2, since the any greater 2 learning rate will most certaintly violate the condition needed for $\bigtriangledown F$ to be considered Lipschitz continuous, which would further mean $F$ is not a contraction mapping, and therefore no guarantee on the existence of a fixed point. That choicing a learning rate greater then $2$ removes the conditions that guarantees that gradient descent converge to the fixed point at the minimum; under said condition gradient descent could converge to the fixed point in k iterations, or diverge from the fixed point in k iteratios.

def plot_decision_boundary(model, X, y):
    figure(figsize=(8, 6), dpi=80)
    # Set min and max values and gives it some padding
    x_min,x_max=X[0,:].min()-0.25,X[0,:].max()+0.25;
    y_min,y_max=X[1, :].min()-0.25,X[1,:].max()+0.25;
    h=0.01;
    # Generates a grid of points with distance h between them
    xx,yy=np.meshgrid(np.arange(x_min,x_max,h),np.arange(y_min,y_max,h));
    # Predict the function value for the whole grid
    Z=model(np.c_[xx.ravel(),yy.ravel()]);
    Z=Z.reshape(xx.shape);
    # Plot the contour and simulated data
    plt.contourf(xx,yy,Z,cmap=plt.cm.Spectral);
    plt.xlabel('$X$');
    plt.ylabel('$Y$');
    plt.scatter(X[0,:],X[1,:],c=y,cmap=plt.cm.Spectral,edgecolor="white");

     One can observe that the contour map that was produced by the neural network logistic regression model captured $99.0$ percent of the simulated data points. This result is exceptionally high, which give rise to the concern that the model is overfitted towards this specific dataset. To test against the notation, we generated a new simulated dataset to validate the model. The result was that there was no great disparsity in accuracy between the first simulated dataset and the second simulated dataset, respectivefully $99.0$ percent accuracy and $98.9$ percent accuracy. From this result we can say with confidence that the model was not overfitted to this first dataset, and that the model seems to possess a high level of generality.

# This is a problem!
# True is numerically 1, and false is numerically 0
# Therefore the neural network predicted false for every applicant 
sum(sum(predictions))
Out[19]:
0

     A major problem resulted, the neural network predicted that none of the accounts would default. This prediction is not realistic, and not predictive of the training data set. Thereforefore the model achieve a zero accurary. What is the issue? How can we fix it?
     The problem is that the applicant data set, the ratio between accounts that have not defaulted in the past 18 months with bank XYZ and accounts that have defaulted are too skewed towards non-default accounts. With this skew in data, the neural network learn to be bais towards the non-default outcome, and thus, the model predicted that none of the account would default.
     The data set contained 14,956 accounts that did not default after Bank XYZ extended credit to them, with 1,697 accounts that Bank XYZ extended credit that defaulted within 18 months. Roughly that is 9 non-defaulted accounts for every 1 defaulted account in the data set; this skew is too much towards non-default.

     In essence, applying neural networks to real world problems is far more trickier then simulated dataset from a theoretical scenario devised by a data scientist. Real world data in most cases is nonlinear and is high dimensional, and when compared to simulated data, whom dimensionality is low and or most time manageably non-linear; which we can observe through the complexity of a real-world credit applicant classification problem. To further this analysis along mathematically, we can refer to the dataset matrix condition numbers, which can explain the sensitivity in the dataset and hence the sensitivity of the model.
     In the following code block, we printed out the matrix condition number for each of the dataframes (e.g. datasets) in this Jupyter notebook. This perfectly illustrates the difference in matrix condition number between the simulated spiral data and the real world data from credit-card applicants, the complexity between each data type is drastic, as it is far easier to resolve a dataset with matrix condition number $1.20$ then it is to resolve a dataset with a condition number of $4.5$ million. To further increase the accuracy of the model, we would have to address the matrix condition number of the real world data, otherwise we could also attempt further tweeks in the model, though this approach might be limited due to the condition number of the dataset. The larger the condition number of a matrix, the more sensitive is the neural network to changes in the learning rate and initial object parameters.
     A further inquiry could resolve the matrix condition number issue of this particular dataset; though the issue could be with the quality of the dataset - the dataset might contain noisy random vectors, or the quality of the dataset might be affected due to the mismatch of the magnitudes between random variables, e.g. one random variables, $X1$, might range from $0$ to $1$, while another random variable, $X2$, might range from $-50,000$ to $300,000$ - such a huge disparsity between magnitudes will contribute to the ill-conditionness of the dataset, and would result in a poor quality dataset and model. As resolution of these issue is not the focus of this project, we will leave further inquiries into this matter for another Jupyter notebook; for now, we will continue to test if the model overfitted the training data.

     In conclusion real-world data-driven problems are far more complicated then low-dimensional and manageably nonlinear simulated data problems, such as the simulated spiral classification problems. In addition the quality of the data utilized during training will effect the quality of the neural network model, and the time required to train it. It is rather crucial to refine one dataset to train a high quality artificial neural network, and particularly, to train a high quality neural network logistic regression model; otherwise as observed a poor dataset, or ill-condition dataset produced poor quality models with very little that can be done to rectify the issue.
     Nonetheless will conclude our inquiry into logistic regression via FFNN, we hope this Jupyter notebook has been useful to the reader and has furthered the reader understanding of neural network and the complexity and challenge of applying such algorithms to real-world data-driven problems.
